        //     So, it's impossible.
        //     return false;
        //   Else (a_i + x >= prev_b):
        //     This means we can reach prev_b.
        //     If a_i + x < m:
        //       We can reach any value in [a_i, a_i + x].
        //       Since a_i < prev_b and a_i + x >= prev_b, we can set b_i = prev_b.
        //       So, prev_b remains prev_b.
        //     If a_i + x >= m:
        //       We can reach any value in [a_i, m-1] and [0, (a_i + x) % m].
        //       Since a_i < prev_b, we need to check if prev_b is reachable.
        //       If (a_i + x) % m < prev_b:
        //         This means prev_b is not in the range [0, (a_i + x) % m].
        //         And since a_i < prev_b, prev_b is also not in [a_i, m-1] (unless prev_b is in [a_i, m-1] and (a_i+x)%m < prev_b, which means we wrapped around but didn't reach prev_b).
        //         This means we cannot satisfy b_i >= prev_b.
        //         return false;
        //       Else ((a_i + x) % m >= prev_b):
        //         We can set b_i = prev_b.
        //         So, prev_b remains prev_b.

        // This can be simplified further.
        // We need to find b_i such that b_i >= prev_b and b_i = (a_i + k) % m for some 0 <= k <= x.
        // If a_i >= prev_b:
        //   We can choose b_i = a_i (k=0). This is the smallest possible b_i.
        //   So, the next prev_b becomes a_i.
        // Else (a_i < prev_b):
        //   We must increment a_i.
        //   We need to check if we can reach prev_b.
        //   The number of increments needed to reach prev_b is (prev_b - a_i).
        //   If (prev_b - a_i) <= x:
        //     We can set b_i = prev_b.
        //     So, the next prev_b remains prev_b.
        //   Else ((prev_b - a_i) > x):
        //     This means we cannot reach prev_b by just incrementing.
        //     We must wrap around.
        //     The maximum value we can reach after wrapping is (a_i + x) % m.
        //     If (a_i + x) % m < prev_b:
        //       It means even with wrapping, we cannot reach prev_b.
        //       So, it's impossible.
        //       return false;
        //     Else ((a_i + x) % m >= prev_b):
        //       We can set b_i = prev_b.
        //       So, the next prev_b remains prev_b.

        // This is the final simplified logic:
        if (current_a >= prev_b) {
            // If a_i is already >= prev_b, we can choose b_i = a_i (0 operations for this element).
            // This is the smallest possible b_i that satisfies b_i >= prev_b.
            // We update prev_b to a_i for the next iteration.
            prev_b = current_a;
        } else { // current_a < prev_b
            // We need to increment a_i.
            // The number of increments needed to reach prev_b is (prev_b - current_a).
            // If (prev_b - current_a) <= x:
            //   We can achieve b_i = prev_b.
            //   So, prev_b remains prev_b.
            // Else ((prev_b - current_a) > x):
            //   We cannot reach prev_b by just incrementing. We must wrap around.
            //   The maximum value we can reach after wrapping is (current_a + x) % m.
            //   If (current_a + x) % m < prev_b:
            //     It means even with wrapping, we cannot reach prev_b.
            //     So, it's impossible.
            //     return false;
            //   Else ((current_a + x) % m >= prev_b):
            //     We can achieve b_i = prev_b.
            //     So, prev_b remains prev_b.
            // This else branch (current_a < prev_b) can be summarized:
            // If (current_a + x) % m < prev_b, then it's impossible.
            // Otherwise, we can set b_i = prev_b.
            // The condition (current_a + x) % m < prev_b is equivalent to:
            // (current_a + x < prev_b) OR (current_a + x >= m AND (current_a + x) % m < prev_b)
            // This is the only case where we fail.
            if ((current_a + x) % m < prev_b) {
                return false;
            }
            // If (current_a + x) % m >= prev_b, we can make b_i = prev_b.
            // So prev_b doesn't change.
        }
    }
    return true;
}

