        // The median of the second class will be a[n]
        // This corresponds to partitioning the sorted array into two halves:
        // [a_0, ..., a_{n-1}] and [a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}]
        // Each half has n elements.
        // If n is odd, then n elements is an odd number of elements.
        // The median of [a_0, ..., a_{n-1}] is a_{(n-1)/2}.
        // The median of [a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}] is a_{n + (n-1)/2}.
        // This is not the general case.
        // The problem states that each class must have an odd number of students.
        // The total number of students is 2n.
        // Let the sizes of the two classes be N1 and N2.
        // N1 + N2 = 2n. N1 and N2 must be odd.
        // The smallest possible odd size is 1.
        // So N1 >= 1, N2 >= 1.
        // The smallest possible N1 is 1, then N2 = 2n-1.
        // The largest possible N1 is 2n-1, then N2 = 1.
        //
        // Consider the sorted array a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // We need to pick a median for the first class, say M1, and a median for the second class, M2.
        // To minimize |M1 - M2|, we should pick M1 and M2 to be as close as possible.
        //
        // Let's consider the elements a_{n-1} and a_n.
        // If we can make a_{n-1} the median of one class and a_n the median of the other class,
        // then the difference would be a_n - a_{n-1}.
