        // and Class 2 takes students with skills a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // Each class has n students.
        // If n is odd, then this is a valid partition.
        // The median of Class 1 (a_0, ..., a_{n-1}) would be a_{(n-1)/2}.
        // The median of Class 2 (a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}) would be a_{n + (n-1)/2}.
        // The difference would be a_{n + (n-1)/2} - a_{(n-1)/2}.
        //
        // However, n can be even. For example, if n=2, 2n=4.
        // Students: a_0, a_1, a_2, a_3.
        // If we split into (a_0, a_1) and (a_2, a_3), each has 2 students (even). Invalid.
        //
        // The key insight is that to minimize the difference between medians,
        // the medians themselves should be chosen from elements that are close in the sorted array.
        //
        // Consider the elements a_{n-1} and a_n.
        // We can always form a class of size $2k_1+1$ and another of size $2k_2+1$ such that $2k_1+1 + 2k_2+1 = 2n$.
        // This means $2(k_1+k_2+1) = 2n$, so $k_1+k_2+1 = n$.
        //
        // We can always construct a partition where a_{n-1} is the median of one class and a_n is the median of the other.
        //
        // Let's try to make a_{n-1} the median of Class 1 and a_n the median of Class 2.
        //
        // Class 1:
        // We need $k_1$ elements smaller than a_{n-1} and $k_1$ elements larger than a_{n-1}.
        // We have $n-1$ elements smaller than a_{n-1} (a_0 to a_{n-2}).
        // We have $n$ elements larger than a_{n-1} (a_n to a_{2n-1}).
        //
        // We can pick $k_1 = 0$. Class 1 = {a_{n-1}}. Size 1. Median a_{n-1}.
        // Then Class 2 must have size $2n-1$.
        // Class 2 needs $k_2 = n-1$ elements smaller than a_n and $k_2 = n-1$ elements larger than a_n.
        // We have $n-1$ elements smaller than a_n (a_0 to a_{n-2}, excluding a_{n-1} which is in Class 1).
        // We have $n-1$ elements larger than a_n (a_{n+1} to a_{2n-1}).
        //
        // So, Class 1 = {a_{n-1}} (size 1, median a_{n-1}).
        // Class 2 = {a_0, ..., a_{n-2}, a_n, a_{n+1}, ..., a_{2n-1}} (size $2n-1$, median a_n).
        // This partition is valid.
        // The difference is $|a_n - a_{n-1}|$.
        //
        // Is it possible to get a smaller difference?
        // Suppose we have two medians $M_1$ and $M_2$.
        // $M_1$ must be some $a_i$ and $M_2$ must be some $a_j$.
        // Without loss of generality, assume $M_1 \le M_2$.
        //
        // For $M_1$ to be a median of a class of size $2k_1+1$, there must be $k_1$ elements smaller than or equal to $M_1$
        // and $k_1$ elements greater than or equal to $M_1$ in that class.
        // Similarly for $M_2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements is $2n$.
        // The elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ are the "smaller half" of the sorted array.
        // The elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are the "larger half" of the sorted array.
        //
        // If both medians $M_1, M_2$ are from the "smaller half" (i.e., $M_1, M_2 \le a_{n-1}$),
        // then to form two classes, we need to pick $2k_1+1$ elements for Class 1 and $2k_2+1$ elements for Class 2.
        // The total number of elements is $2n$.
        // If $M_1 \le M_2 \le a_{n-1}$, then there are at least $n$ elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ that are all greater than or equal to $M_2$.
        // These $n$ elements must be distributed between the two classes.
        // Each class needs $k_i$ elements larger than its median.
        // So, $k_1$ elements larger than $M_1$ and $k_2$ elements larger than $M_2$.
        // The total number of elements larger than $M_1$ or $M_2$ is at least $n$.
        //
        // This argument is a bit hand-wavy. A more formal argument:
        // Let $M_1$ and $M_2$ be the medians of the two classes, $C_1$ and $C_2$.
        // Let $|C_1| = 2k_1+1$ and $|C_2| = 2k_2+1$.
        // $M_1$ is the $(k_1+1)$-th element of $C_1$ when sorted.
        // $M_2$ is the $(k_2+1)$-th element of $C_2$ when sorted.
        //
        // There are $k_1$ elements in $C_1$ less than or equal to $M_1$.
        // There are $k_1$ elements in $C_1$ greater than or equal to $M_1$.
        // Similarly for $C_2$.
        //
        // Consider the elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ and $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // There are $n$ elements in the first group and $n$ in the second.
        //
        // If $M_1$ and $M_2$ are both from $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$, say $M_1 = a_i, M_2 = a_j$ with $i,j < n$.
        // Then all elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are greater than or equal to $M_1$ and $M_2$.
        // There are $n$ such elements.
        // These $n$ elements must be distributed into $C_1$ and $C_2$.
        // $C_1$ needs $k_1$ elements $\ge M_1$. $C_2$ needs $k_2$ elements $\ge M_2$.
        // So, $k_1+k_2$ elements must be $\ge \max(M_1, M_2)$.
        // We know $k_1+k_2+1 = n$. So $k_1+k_2 = n-1$.
        // This means we need $n-1$ elements $\ge \max(M_1, M_2)$.
        // We have $n$ elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ that are $\ge a_n > a_{n-1} \ge \max(M_1, M_2)$.
        // This is possible.
        //
        // However, if $M_1, M_2 \le a_{n-1}$, then $M_2 \le a_{n-1}$.
        // The elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are all strictly greater than $a_{n-1}$.
        // So they are all strictly greater than $M_2$.
        // These $n$ elements must be distributed.
        // $C_1$ needs $k_1$ elements $\ge M_1$. $C_2$ needs $k_2$ elements $\ge M_2$.
        // The total number of elements $\ge M_2$ is $n$ (from $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$).
        // If $M_1, M_2$ are both from $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$, then $M_2 \le a_{n-1}$.
        // The elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are all greater than $M_2$.
        // These $n$ elements must be distributed between $C_1$ and $C_2$.
        // $C_1$ needs $k_1$ elements greater than $M_1$. $C_2$ needs $k_2$ elements greater than $M_2$.
        // The total number of elements greater than $M_1$ or $M_2$ is at least $n$.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that one median must be $\le a_{n-1}$ and the other must be $\ge a_n$.
        // Proof by contradiction:
        // Assume both medians $M_1, M_2$ are $\le a_{n-1}$.
        // Then $M_1 \le M_2 \le a_{n-1}$.
        // Class $C_2$ has $k_2$ elements greater than or equal to $M_2$.
        // All elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are strictly greater than $a_{n-1}$, hence strictly greater than $M_2$.
        // There are $n$ such elements.
        // These $n$ elements must be distributed between $C_1$ and $C_2$.
        // $C_1$ needs $k_1$ elements $\ge M_1$. $C_2$ needs $k_2$ elements $\ge M_2$.
        // The total number of elements greater than or equal to $M_2$ (and thus $M_1$) is at least $n$.
        // The elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are all greater than $M_2$.
        // So, $k_1$ elements from $C_1$ and $k_2$ elements from $C_2$ must come from $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // This means $k_1+k_2 \le n$.
        // We know $k_1+k_2 = n-1$. This is consistent.
        //
        // However, consider the elements smaller than $M_1$.
        // There are $k_1$ elements in $C_1$ less than or equal to $M_1$.
        // There are $k_2$ elements in $C_2$ less than or equal to $M_2$.
        // The total number of elements less than or equal to $M_2$ is $i+1$ if $M_2=a_i$.
        // Since $M_2 \le a_{n-1}$, $i \le n-1$.
        // So there are at most $n$ elements less than or equal to $M_2$.
        // The total number of elements less than or equal to $M_1$ or $M_2$ is $k_1+k_2$.
        // This means $k_1+k_2 \le n$.
        //
        // The crucial point is that the $n$ smallest elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ and the $n$ largest elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$
        // must be split.
        //
        // Let $M_1$ be the median of $C_1$ and $M_2$ be the median of $C_2$.
        // WLOG, $M_1 \le M_2$.
        //
        // The number of elements $\le M_1$ in $C_1$ is $k_1$.
        // The number of elements $\ge M_1$ in $C_1$ is $k_1$.
        // The number of elements $\le M_2$ in $C_2$ is $k_2$.
        // The number of elements $\ge M_2$ in $C_2$ is $k_2$.
        //
        // Consider the elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$. There are $n$ of them.
        // Consider the elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$. There are $n$ of them.
        //
        // If $M_1$ and $M_2$ are both in $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$, then $M_2 \le a_{n-1}$.
        // All elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are strictly greater than $M_2$.
        // These $n$ elements must be distributed between $C_1$ and $C_2$.
        // $C_1$ must contain $k_1$ elements $\ge M_1$. $C_2$ must contain $k_2$ elements $\ge M_2$.
        // Since $M_1 \le M_2$, any element $\ge M_2$ is also $\ge M_1$.
        // So, $k_1$ elements from $C_1$ and $k_2$ elements from $C_2$ must be chosen from $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // This means $k_1+k_2$ elements must be chosen from $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // Since $k_1+k_2 = n-1$, this is possible.
        //
        // Now consider elements smaller than $M_1$.
        // There are $k_1$ elements in $C_1$ that are $\le M_1$.
        // There are $k_2$ elements in $C_2$ that are $\le M_2$.
        // The total number of elements $\le M_2$ is at most $n$ (since $M_2 \le a_{n-1}$).
        // The total number of elements $\le M_1$ or $\le M_2$ is $k_1+k_2$.
        // This means $k_1+k_2 \le n$. This is also consistent.
        //
        // The argument is simpler:
        // The median of a set of $2k+1$ numbers is the $(k+1)$-th smallest.
        // This means there are $k$ numbers less than or equal to it, and $k$ numbers greater than or equal to it.
        //
        // Let $M_1$ and $M_2$ be the medians. WLOG $M_1 \le M_2$.
        // $M_1$ is the $(k_1+1)$-th element of $C_1$. $M_2$ is the $(k_2+1)$-th element of $C_2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements less than $M_1$ in $C_1$ is $k_1$.
        // The total number of elements less than $M_2$ in $C_2$ is $k_2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements greater than $M_1$ in $C_1$ is $k_1$.
        // The total number of elements greater than $M_2$ in $C_2$ is $k_2$.
        //
        // Summing up:
        // Total elements less than $M_1$ (or $M_2$ if $M_1=M_2$) is at least $k_1$.
        // Total elements greater than $M_2$ (or $M_1$ if $M_1=M_2$) is at least $k_2$.
        //
        // Consider the elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ and $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // There are $n$ elements in the first group, $n$ in the second.
        //
        // If $M_1$ and $M_2$ are both from $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$, then $M_2 \le a_{n-1}$.
        // All elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are strictly greater than $M_2$.
        // These $n$ elements must contain all elements in $C_1$ that are $>M_1$ and all elements in $C_2$ that are $>M_2$.
        // So, $k_1+k_2$ elements must be chosen from $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // Since $k_1+k_2 = n-1$, this is possible.
        //
        // Now consider elements smaller than $M_1$.
        // There are $k_1$ elements in $C_1$ that are $<M_1$.
        // There are $k_2$ elements in $C_2$ that are $<M_2$.
        // The total number of elements less than $M_1$ in the entire array is at most $n-1$ (since $M_1 \le a_{n-1}$).
        // The total number of elements less than $M_2$ in the entire array is at most $n-1$.
        // The total number of elements less than $M_1$ or $M_2$ is $k_1+k_2$.
        // This means $k_1+k_2 \le n-1$. This is consistent.
        //
        // The crucial point is that if both medians are in the "lower half" ($a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$),
        // then the $n$ elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are all greater than both medians.
        // These $n$ elements must provide the "greater than median" counts for both classes.
        // So $k_1+k_2$ elements must come from $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$. This is $n-1$ elements.
        // This is fine.
        //
        // If both medians are in the "upper half" ($a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$),
        // then $M_1 \ge a_n$.
        // All elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ are strictly smaller than $M_1$.
        // These $n$ elements must provide the "smaller than median" counts for both classes.
        // So $k_1+k_2$ elements must come from $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$. This is $n-1$ elements.
        // This is also fine.
        //
        // The minimum difference is always $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // This is because we can always construct the partition:
        // Class 1: $\{a_{n-1}\}$ (size 1, median $a_{n-1}$)
        // Class 2: $\{a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}, a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$ (size $2n-1$, median $a_n$)
        //
        // This works because:
        // Class 1 has 1 element, which is odd. Its median is $a_{n-1}$.
        // Class 2 has $2n-1$ elements, which is odd.
        // To find its median, we need to sort its elements:
        // $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-2}, a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // The number of elements is $2n-1$. So $k_2 = (2n-1-1)/2 = n-1$.
        // The median is the $(k_2+1)$-th element, which is the $n$-th element.
        // The elements are $a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}$ (total $n-1$ elements).
        // The $n$-th element is $a_n$.
        // So the median of Class 2 is $a_n$.
        //
        // This partition is always valid and achieves difference $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // Any other partition would involve medians $M_1, M_2$.
        // If $M_1, M_2$ are chosen such that $M_1 \le a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 \ge a_n$, then $|M_1 - M_2| \ge a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // If both $M_1, M_2 \le a_{n-1}$, then $M_2 \le a_{n-1}$.
        // If both $M_1, M_2 \ge a_n$, then $M_1 \ge a_n$.
        //
        // The minimum difference is indeed $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // This is a standard result for problems asking to split into two groups and minimize difference of medians.
        // The two medians will always be the two middle elements of the sorted array.

        long long result = a[n] - a[n - 1];
        std::cout << result << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}

