        // If (x,y) -> (x+1,y+1) and (x+1,y+1) -> (x,y), this uses 2 diagonal moves.
        // If (x,y) -> (x+1,y) and (x+1,y) -> (x,y), this uses 0 diagonal moves.
        // We want to maximize diagonal moves. So we prefer the first type of cancellation.
        // We have (k - m) moves to waste.
        // If (k - m) is even, we can make (k - m) / 2 pairs of diagonal moves that cancel out.
        // Each pair contributes 2 diagonal moves. So total (k - m) diagonal moves from wasting.
        // Total diagonal moves = n (to reach (n,n)) + (k - m) (from wasting).
        // This simplifies to k - (m - n).
        // If (k - m) is odd, we cannot make all (k - m) moves diagonal.
        // One move must be an axial move that is cancelled by another axial move.
        // For example, (x,y) -> (x+1,y) -> (x,y). This uses 2 moves, 0 diagonal.
        // If we have an odd number of moves to waste, say 1, we can't make it diagonal.
        // We must use one axial move and then return.
